  "sourceType": "PUBLIC_DOMAIN",
  "sourceNotes": "Lane cake was created by Emma Rylander Lane of Clayton, Alabama, who published the recipe as 'Prize Cake' in 'Some Good Things to Eat' (1898). The cake won first prize at the Columbus, Georgia county fair. It became a Southern classic and appears in numerous regional American cookbooks of the early twentieth century, including Fannie Farmer's later editions. The bourbon content varies by tradition; the original recipe uses 1 cup (240 ml) of whiskey in the filling.",
